AB  - Members of the Bacteroidetes are commonly known for their capacity to degrade complex organic matter including plant polymers. There are a number of marine strains within this phylum, but relatively few that have been isolated from salt marshes. The two strains described here were taken from salt marsh sediments along the Atlantic coast of Virginia. They were isolated from end dilution plates (10-5-10-6 dilutions) for aerobic heterotrophs and are part of a collection of 38 strains of Bacteroidetes that were collected from four different salt marsh sites at the same or different times. Both strains are short rods that were catalase and oxidase positive, and required NaCl to grow. Both strains reduced nitrate, but did not ferment; they have a limited number of single carbon sources they can utilize, including glucose, and cellobiose. G. salipaludis, strain BSD S2-05, was yellow pigmented with a temperature growth range of 10 to 37degreeC, and tolerated salt concentrations of up to 3%. The dominant fatty acids were 15:0 ISO, 15:0 ISO G, 15:0 ISO 3OH and 17:0 ISO 3OH. It did not contain flexirubins. The G+C content was 32.9%. Sequence analysis of its SSU rRNA gene indicated that it was 94% related to Gelidibacter algens. It was representative of a group of closely related strains that comprised 10 out of the 38 isolates of Bacteroidetes, suggesting this group is especially well adapted for growing in salt marsh sediments. C. virginiensis, strain BSB S2-03 is salmon-colored, has a temperature growth range of 4 to 42degreeC and tolerated salt concentrations of up to 7% NaCl. The dominant fatty acids were 15:0 ISO, 15:0 ISO 2OH, and 16:1 w7c. The G+C content was 34.6%, and it was 94.8% similar to Cyclobacterium sp. by comparison of 16S rDNA. This strain was not closely related to any of the other 38 isolates.
