AB  - A Functional and Structural Trajectory (FAST) model is presented that predicts the evolution of wetland structure and function during salt marsh ecosystem development. The FAST model is tested by comparing structural and functional attributes of marsh producers (Spartina), consumers (benthic invertebrates) and nutrient cycles (C, N, P) along a chronosequence of 1 to 28 year-old constructed Spartina alterniflora a marshes with paired older reference (natural) marshes. Salt marsh structure and function followed two inherently different trajectories during ecosystem development. Functional attributes, like Spartina biomass, invertebrate density and carbon and nutrient accumulation, exceeded 100% equivalence before decreasing to levels found in reference marshes. In contrast, structural attributes like Spartina stem density and height, invertebrate species richness and soil carbon and nutrient pools gradually converged to equivalence without ever exceeding levels in reference marshes. Our trajectories also revealed that different components of the restored salt marsh ecosystem developed at different rates. Both Spartina structure and function achieved equivalence to reference wetlands within 10-15 years following establishment. Development of invertebrate structure and function required 15-20 years. Soil C and nutrient accumulation occurred almost instantaneously with colonization by Spartina. However, after 28 years, soil C and N pools were considerably less than in reference marshes. Our FAST model demonstrates that trajectories can be developed and used to predict the evolution of salt marsh structure and function during wetland ecosystem development. The model should be tested using similar ecosystems in different geographic regions and in other detritus based ecosystems to evaluate its predictive power and robustness.
