AB  - Sediments have been sampled in seven Tagus estuary salt marshes at three depths: 0-5 cm, 15-25 cm (zone of higher root density), and 45-55 cm (below the roots). Collection was done in areas colonised by Spartina maritima, Halimione portulacoides and Arthrocnenum fruticosum. Concentrations of zinc, lead, copper, cadmium and loss on ignition were determined, as well as the fraction of metals extracted by DTPA. Metal concentrations were not correlated to LOI, and enrichment factors (defined as the ratio of metal concentration in the 0-5 cm and 45-55 cm layers) were higher in salt marshes closer to the anthropogenic sources. However, the fraction of metals extracted by DTPA in sediment between roots was inversely correlated to LOI. This suggests that metals are more easily uptaken by the plants as organic matter in the sediments degrades.
