AB  - Growth and maturation of transplanted salt marshes is often limited by the availability of nitrogen (N). We examined the role of N-2-fixing benthic microbial assemblages (microalgae and associated bacteria) in two restored marshes (l-year-old and 6-year-old marsh) and a natural salt marsh in the Newport River Estuary, North Carolina. Benthic N, fixation (nitrogenase activity NA), chlorophyll a (Chl a concentration, Spartina alterniflora (smooth cordgrass) stem counts, and sediment organic matter content were determined in the three marshes. Significant differences were observed between sites for both Chi a and NA. The 1-year-old marsh always exhibited the highest levels of NA and Chi a. Sediment organic matter content was lowest in the 1-year-old marsh (similar to 2%), intermediate in the 6-year-old marsh (similar to 5%), and highest in the natural marsh (similar to 10%). Carbon and nitrogen analyses were also performed on the 1-year-old marsh sediments, which were depleted in N. a positive correlation was observed between surface sediment N and Chi a. Remineralized, microbially derived N may provide growth-limiting inorganic N to Spartina transplants. N-2-fixing microbial assemblages in the 1-year-old marsh may also be an important food source for marsh infauna. Benthic N-2-fixing microbial assemblages play a key role in the N economy of restored salt marshes.
