AB  - The USDA/SCS in 1984 determined that there were 26 ecological communities in Florida. Using soil series names and possible plants in specific ecological communities from this study, sites were chosen from a soil characterization study. The objectives of this study were: 1) to determine the approximate relative natural background P concentrations in the A horizon of six ecological communities; 2) to group the ecological communities according to P concentration and 3) to correlate other soil parameters to P concentrations. Eighty-nine surface soils (A horizons) from six of these communities which included freshwater marshes, swamp, hardwoods, salt water marshes, south Florida flatwoods, north Florida flatwoods, and sloughs were selected. The communities had water table depths <1 m. Some communities were submerged under water part of the year. Geometric means of total soil P (TP) using a hypobromite determination ranged from 23 mg kg(-1) in the sloughs to 438 mg kg(-1) in the salt marshes. Soil extractable P (EP) using Mehlich I extracting solution ranged from 4.7 mg kg(-1) in the north Florida flatwoods to 64.5 mg kg(-1) in the salt water marshes. Using statistical analysis, the six communities could be separated in distinct groups. Using TP, the first group included swamp hardwoods, fresh water marshes and salt marshes, and the second group was south Florida flatwoods, north Florida flatwoods, and sloughs. A similar relationship was found for the EP. The correlation coefficient between EP and TP was r = 0.77. Correlations with other soil properties (clay, organic carbon, total Al, total Fe, total Ca) were also made, and the communities were found to be grouped in the same way as they did with EP and TP. This suggests that ecological communities can be grouped according to soil characteristics.
