AB  - This chapter examines the geochemistry of carbon and the nutrient elements (nitrogen, phosphorus, and silicon) in the sediments of estuaries and near-coastal seas. The emphasis is on the sources, storage, and transformations that occur in sediments during storage on decadal to centennial timescales. Stable isotopes of carbon, nitrogen, silicon, and phosphate are used to help differentiate sources and to help predict the effects of early diagenesis in the sediment stores. The principal sediment stores of C, N, P, and Si are muds and silts of shoal water or inner-shelf river deltas and non-deltaic, often estuarine, coasts. These stores comprise coastal mud banks (sub-tidal/intertidal), salt marshes, mangroves, and seagrass meadows. The influence of human management of the coastal zone is reviewed, especially with respect to increasing sediment storage capacity, carbon burial, and greenhouse gas production.
