AB  - Sulfate-reducing bacteria (SRB) dominate the mineralization of organic matter in salt marsh environments where they are believed to be represented by two phylogenetically distinct groups, Gram-positive bacteria and delta-Proteobacteria. We assessed the 16S rRNA diversity of delta-Proteobacterial SRB in salt marsh sediments of Plum Island Sound, MA by PCR, cloning and sequencing. Six samples taken over the course of a year were extracted to ensure representation of shifts in SRB community tied to seasonal growth cycles of the marsh grass Spartina. A clone library was constructed using 385F (selective for delta-Proteobacterial SRB) and 1492R (general bacteria) primers. Phylogenetic relationships were determined by the neighbor-joining method, whereas overall sampling efficiency and diversity were estimated using rarefaction analysis and the Chao-1 richness estimator. The primers also amplified other groups, such as epsilon-Proteobacteria, Firmicutes, and Cytophaga/Flexibacter, since the primer target sequences that are shared by almost all delta-Proteobacterial SRB, also occur in representatives of other bacterial lineages. We analyzed more than 1,000 sequences and over 50% belonged to members of delta-Proteobacteria. Among the delta-Proteobacteria, most of the ribotypes (unique 16S rRNA sequences) were associated with members of the Desulfobacteriaceae (Desulfosarcina, Desulfobacterium and Desulfonema) and Desulfobulbaceae (Desulfobulbus, Desulfofustis and Desulfotalea) group. Sequences from the Desulfomicrobiaceae and Desulfoarculaceae groups were also observed. Over two thirds of the delta-Proteobacterial ribotypes were most similar to Desulfosarcina and Desulfobacterium, suggesting that complete oxidizers dominate this environment. This is supported by a previous study in which Desulfobacteriaceae accounted for up to 2 5% of the total Bacteria rRNA in the marsh sediments. Furthermore, no close relatives of Desulfovibrio were detected, despite their sequence 